00:14:08,959 --> 00:14:14,559
Then, do you know if your brother and Mr. Hiramune knew each other?

263
00:14:14,559 --> 00:14:17,359
I wonder but I don't think so.

264
00:14:20,059 --> 00:14:21,659
Saturday night.

265
00:14:22,659 --> 00:14:26,959
Did you brother meet with anyone on Saturday nights?

266
00:14:26,959 --> 00:14:30,459
Yes. The wife of my late brother

267
00:14:30,459 --> 00:14:32,859
who died the year before last used to say

268
00:14:32,859 --> 00:14:36,959
that he didn't come home on Saturday nights,

269
00:14:36,959 --> 00:14:38,659
but rather, frequently came back the next morning.

270
00:14:38,659 --> 00:14:41,359
Thinking that he may be having an extra-marital affair,

271
00:14:41,359 --> 00:14:43,859
his wife persistently rang his pocket bell.

272
00:14:43,859 --> 00:14:48,759
It seems that he called her back but was outraged

273
00:14:48,759 --> 00:14:52,759
telling her that he was at the doctor so not to bug him.

274
00:14:52,759 --> 00:14:54,959
Doctor? Could it have been Dr. Bokawa

275
00:14:54,959 --> 00:14:57,959
who was the first person that was killed?

276
00:14:57,959 --> 00:15:01,459
Yes. A police detective said the same thing 20 years ago

277
00:15:01,459 --> 00:15:04,059
and seemed to be investigating the case.

278
00:15:04,059 --> 00:15:08,759
My brother's name wasn't on the patient list of that doctor, was it?

279
00:15:08,759 --> 00:15:11,059
I guess not.

280
00:15:18,559 --> 00:15:20,559
How was it, Officer Takagi?

281
00:15:20,559 --> 00:15:22,259
Did you find anything?

282
00:15:22,259 --> 00:15:23,659
Nothing at all.

283
00:15:24,859 --> 00:15:26,559
Ayumi and Ai, what do you think?

284
00:15:26,559 --> 00:15:29,159
Didn't the man just now look a lot like the killer?

285
00:15:29,159 --> 00:15:32,459
I didn't think he resembled the killer in particular.

286
00:15:32,459 --> 00:15:35,559
I don't think lady is the killer either.

287
00:15:35,559 --> 00:15:38,659
Well, I guess if he were wearing a long haired wig and mustache

288
00:15:38,659 --> 00:15:41,559
like the time we passed him,

289
00:15:41,559 --> 00:15:43,659
he would probably make a different impression, though.

290
00:15:43,659 --> 00:15:45,059
True.

291
00:15:45,059 --> 00:15:47,459
Where next?

292
00:15:47,459 --> 00:15:49,159
The last place we're going

293
00:15:49,159 --> 00:15:51,859
to go is to the house of Eiki Nabei,

294
00:15:51,859 --> 00:15:54,059
the son of the lawyer, Mr. Susumu Nabei,

295
00:15:54,059 --> 00:15:56,159
who was killed five years after the serial killings

296
00:15:56,159 --> 00:15:57,759
that occurred 20 years ago.

297
00:16:10,851 --> 00:16:13,851
Eiki who was 10 years old back then,

298
00:16:13,851 --> 00:16:15,651
was in his room when he was awakened

299
00:16:15,651 --> 00:16:18,151
by the sound of his father groaning.

300
00:16:18,151 --> 00:16:19,851
And, after the killer left,

301
00:16:19,851 --> 00:16:23,251
he says that he was so terrified that he couldn't come of his room

302
00:16:23,251 --> 00:16:25,751
until his mother came back from shopping.

303
00:16:25,751 --> 00:16:28,751
His mother, after finding her husband lying dead

304
00:16:28,751 --> 00:16:30,551
became bed-ridden because of the shock,

305
00:16:30,551 --> 00:16:32,251
and still seems to be in the hospital even now.

306
00:16:32,251 --> 00:16:36,851
So, Eiki seems to be living alone in that house now.

307
00:16:36,851 --> 00:16:39,451
Will you please give me a break, officer!

308
00:16:39,451 --> 00:16:42,651
I've talked more than enough about the incident in the past!

309
00:16:42,651 --> 00:16:45,251
"Eiki Nabei (25)" -I'm sick and tired of the media coming after me

310
00:16:45,251 --> 00:16:48,551
saying that the case is about to expire and all!

311
00:16:48,551 --> 00:16:50,151
I could care less if the killer

312
00:16:50,151 --> 00:16:53,751
who killed my father is going after a new target!

313
00:16:53,751 --> 00:16:56,051
Then, then...

314
00:16:56,051 --> 00:17:00,651
At least please tell me if your father knew Mr. Hiramune...

315
00:17:00,651 --> 00:17:02,651
Who knows? Stupid!

316
00:17:02,651 --> 00:17:03,951
Stupid?

317
00:17:09,151 --> 00:17:12,651
It seems he wasn't like that before.

318
00:17:12,651 --> 00:17:13,751
Really?

319
00:17:13,751 --> 00:17:14,751
Yes.

320
00:17:14,751 --> 00:17:16,351
According to the police,

321
00:17:16,351 --> 00:17:18,151
be it about what happened on the day of the incident

322
00:17:18,151 --> 00:17:20,551
or the strange thing that his father was saying

323
00:17:20,551 --> 00:17:22,251
before he was killed.

324
00:17:22,251 --> 00:17:23,951
He used to come to the police

325
00:17:23,951 --> 00:17:25,951
and report every little thing he remembered.

326
00:17:27,151 --> 00:17:28,851
Strange thing?

327
00:17:28,851 --> 00:17:31,551
It seems he used to sleep till noon on Sundays,

328
00:17:31,551 --> 00:17:34,551
and mumble when he got up.

329
00:17:34,551 --> 00:17:36,351
"I had a tough time last night because the dealer (head of the house)

330
00:17:36,351 --> 00:17:39,151
went out with a big hand!(was run over)"

331
00:17:39,151 --> 00:17:42,351
So, somebody's parent was run over by a car.

332
00:17:42,351 --> 00:17:45,651
I see, after all, he was a lawyer.

333
00:17:45,651 --> 00:17:47,151
He must've been handling the case of either

334
00:17:47,151 --> 00:17:49,451
the plaintiff or the defendant.

335
00:17:49,451 --> 00:17:52,951
So? How does that end up being a strange story?

336
00:17:52,951 --> 00:17:57,051
Well, Mr. Nabei who was killed specialized in business law

337
00:17:57,051 --> 00:18:00,251
and didn't handle cases having to do with traffic accidents.

338
00:18:01,351 --> 00:18:02,751
Then, why?

339
00:18:02,751 --> 00:18:04,551
That's why Eiki thought it strange

340
00:18:04,551 --> 00:18:07,451
and reported it to the police.

341
00:18:09,451 --> 00:18:11,551
A cry baby.

342
00:18:11,551 --> 00:18:13,951
At the doctor.

343
00:18:13,951 --> 00:18:16,251
The dealer goes out.

344
00:18:17,451 --> 00:18:18,751
So, I see.

345
00:18:21,251 --> 00:18:23,351
I've finally figured out

346
00:18:23,351 --> 00:18:25,851
the connection of the four victims.

347
00:18:25,851 --> 00:18:26,851
What?

348
00:18:30,051 --> 00:18:31,651
Mahjong?

349
00:18:31,651 --> 00:18:35,851
Are you saying that the thing in common all the four people

350
00:18:35,851 --> 00:18:37,851
who were killed had is mahjong?

351
00:18:37,851 --> 00:18:42,151
Mr. Hiramune said on the wide show on TV, didn't he?

352
00:18:42,151 --> 00:18:44,151
That "it's all last",

353
00:18:44,151 --> 00:18:47,351
or he was getting rid of "anko" to finish that round of the game.

354
00:18:47,351 --> 00:18:50,651
These are all terminology used in mahjong, aren't they?

355
00:18:50,651 --> 00:18:54,051
I'm sure that Mr. Hiramune loves mahjong.

356
00:18:54,051 --> 00:18:58,051
I... I guess so, but what about the other three?

357
00:18:58,051 --> 00:19:01,651
As to Mr. Bokawa, who was the first one killed,

358
00:19:01,651 --> 00:19:04,351
when he came home drunk on Saturday night complaining,

359
00:19:04,351 --> 00:19:08,751
"How dare they make fun of me calling me cry baby."

360
00:19:08,751 --> 00:19:11,451
Assistant professor, Mugita of the science and technology department,

361
00:19:11,451 --> 00:19:14,751
after being called on his beeper by his wife,

362
00:19:14,751 --> 00:19:16,151
retuned her call shouting,

363
00:19:16,151 --> 00:19:20,351
"I'm almost ready to win the game. Don't bug me!"

364
00:19:20,351 --> 00:19:22,151
Lawyer Nabei seems to have slept frequently till noon on Sundays,

365
00:19:22,151 --> 00:19:24,751
and when he got up would mumble,

366
00:19:24,751 --> 00:19:30,551
"The dealer won the game with a big hand, right?"

367
00:19:30,551 --> 00:19:32,951
When Mr. Bokawa said they called him a cry baby,

368
00:19:32,951 --> 00:19:34,851
it meant that he'd frequently pick up the tiles of other people

369
00:19:34,851 --> 00:19:37,751
-and display part of his hand in the game. -Why does he have to cry?

370
00:19:37,751 --> 00:19:39,951
It's a game called Mahjong, isn't it?

371
00:19:39,951 --> 00:19:42,551
To cry, "naku" is when a person,

372
00:19:42,551 --> 00:19:45,751
in order to win the game as soon as possible,

373
00:19:45,751 --> 00:19:48,151
picks a tile that someone disposes of on the table up

374
00:19:48,151 --> 00:19:49,751
to make a pair of threes or fours.

375
00:19:49,751 --> 00:19:51,951
Which means that phrase that Mr. Nabei mentioned about,

376
00:19:51,951 --> 00:19:54,251
"I was in a fix because the parent was run over" was...

377
00:19:54,251 --> 00:19:58,251
Maybe that phrase, "The parent was run over" was taken mistakenly

378
00:19:58,251 --> 00:20:01,151
by his the son, Eiki?

379
00:20:01,151 --> 00:20:03,551
"Parent" means the dealer of the mahjong game

380
00:20:03,551 --> 00:20:05,751
who gets to score a lot of points.

381
00:20:05,751 --> 00:20:06,851
"Run over" means the points of the person

382
00:20:06,851 --> 00:20:08,751
who wins the game gets higher.

383
00:20:08,751 --> 00:20:10,651
It means that a hand called "Haneman" is played and the player wins.

384
00:20:10,651 --> 00:20:13,751
So, he meant, the dealer won with a high point,

385
00:20:13,751 --> 00:20:16,351
which put him a fix.

386
00:20:16,351 --> 00:20:18,551
Then what does Mr. Mugita's remark,

387
00:20:18,551 --> 00:20:22,251
"I'm at the doctor now" mean?

388
00:20:22,251 --> 00:20:23,851
He probably said,

389
00:20:23,851 --> 00:20:25,451
"I'll be winning the game with just two more tiles now!

390
00:20:25,451 --> 00:20:28,951
Don't bother me!"

391
00:20:30,151 --> 00:20:31,251
True.

392
00:20:31,251 --> 00:20:34,051
It sounds like "I'm at the doctor now" to me, though.

393
00:20:34,051 --> 00:20:37,251
What does that means?

394
00:20:37,251 --> 00:20:41,551
When you need only two more tiles to go win the game,

395
00:20:41,551 --> 00:20:44,651
you call it "Iishanten"!

396
00:20:44,651 --> 00:20:46,251
In other words, he's angry and saying,

397
00:20:46,251 --> 00:20:47,451
"I'm almost ready to win the game,

398
00:20:47,451 --> 00:20:50,551
so don't call me on the beeper and bother me"

399
00:20:50,551 --> 00:20:54,051
Well, all the terminologies used are for mahjong,

400
00:20:54,051 --> 00:20:56,751
so if a person who never played mahjong heard wrong,

401
00:20:56,751 --> 00:20:58,551
it's understandable.

402
00:20:58,551 --> 00:21:00,151
True.

403
00:21:00,151 --> 00:21:02,451
Because the ones who heard so, were Mrs. Bohkawa,

404
00:21:02,451 --> 00:21:09,351
Mrs. Mugita and Mr. Nabei's son, Eiki who was still a child.

405
00:21:09,351 --> 00:21:10,551
If you think of it that way,

406
00:21:10,551 --> 00:21:12,751
the remark the culprit spit out,

407
00:21:12,751 --> 00:21:14,151
that Eiki heard was about mahjong too, then.

408
00:21:14,151 --> 00:21:15,551
Remark he spit out?

409
00:21:15,551 --> 00:21:21,151
It seems that Eiki heard the words of the culprit who left the house.

410
00:21:21,151 --> 00:21:22,851
You're just paying me to take responsibility,

411
00:21:22,851 --> 00:21:24,751
so don't blame it on me.

412
00:21:24,751 --> 00:21:28,751
You're to blame for doing something like that.

413
00:21:28,751 --> 00:21:34,251
I was cornered by the police who left this big scar on me.

414
00:21:34,251 --> 00:21:36,551
Taking responsibility (sekininbarai) and cornered (tenpai)

415
00:21:36,551 --> 00:21:38,651
are also words used in mahjong.

416
00:21:38,651 --> 00:21:41,951
And? What from there?

417
00:21:41,951 --> 00:21:43,651
What else?

418
00:21:43,651 --> 00:21:45,451
There's a very high possibility

419
00:21:45,451 --> 00:21:46,751
that the four were sitting around

420
00:21:46,751 --> 00:21:49,251
a mahjong table somewhere every Saturday.

421
00:21:49,251 --> 00:21:50,451
Narrow the mahjong parlours down

422
00:21:50,451 --> 00:21:53,251
to ones that the four could've dropped by from their houses

423
00:21:53,251 --> 00:21:57,251
or work place 20 years ago and ask around.

424
00:21:57,251 --> 00:21:59,851
As far as mahjong is concerned,

425
00:21:59,851 --> 00:22:01,451
people can play together

426
00:22:01,451 --> 00:22:04,151
no matter what the difference in age is.

427
00:22:05,751 --> 00:22:07,251
Okay!

428
00:22:07,251 --> 00:22:12,251
Youth Detective Squad! Let's go!

429
00:22:12,251 --> 00:22:15,651
It's getting late, you know. Is it okay?

430
00:22:15,651 --> 00:22:17,651
It's already 9 pm.

431
00:22:17,651 --> 00:22:18,951
Yeah, don't worry about it.

432
00:22:18,951 --> 00:22:22,251
I told mother that I'd be spending the night at doctor's house tonight.

433
00:22:22,251 --> 00:22:24,551
No problem.

434
00:22:24,551 --> 00:22:25,851
Really?

435
00:22:27,751 --> 00:22:29,851
Okay! Let's get going!

436
00:22:29,851 --> 00:22:31,151
Aye!

437
00:22:36,651 --> 00:22:39,051
Hold on, whistling man.

438
00:22:39,051 --> 00:22:42,451
I'll expose you're true identity for sure.

439
00:24:04,451 --> 00:24:06,451
His address is unknown and he's unemployed.

440
00:24:06,451 --> 00:24:07,851
His name is...

441
00:24:07,851 --> 00:24:09,551
Dokuro Kibo.

442
00:24:09,551 --> 00:24:13,751
The letter Z that was left on Mr. Hiramune's back's bugging me.

443
00:24:13,751 --> 00:24:15,751
So that person is a cat.

444
00:24:16,851 --> 00:24:20,351
Be on full guard when coming in contact with him.

445
00:24:20,351 --> 00:24:24,851
Listen! Life is lost in a split second.

446
00:24:24,851 --> 00:24:28,551
I guess I'm the only hostage left.

447
00:24:28,551 --> 00:24:30,051
Next Conan,

448
00:24:30,051 --> 00:24:33,951
"An Old Scar and the Soul of a Detective"

449
00:24:49,951 --> 00:24:52,451
Next Conan's Hint:

450
00:24:52,451 --> 00:24:54,051
"Mouse".

451
00:24:54,051 --> 00:24:55,951
Why do they call it a mouse?

452
00:24:55,951 --> 00:24:57,451
You'll find out next episode.

453
00:24:57,451 --> 00:24:59,039
Genta, your mouth looks funny.

